    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the Wikipedia article provided, here is the extracted information:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Complete Timeline of Events\n\n- **August 2023**: A bidding war for U.S. Steel begins. Cleveland-Cliffs makes an early offer of $7.8 billion, which U.S. Steel declines. Other bids emerge from ArcelorMittal, Stelco, and Esmark (withdrawn).\n- **December 18, 2023**: Nippon Steel (NSC) announces it has agreed to buy U.S. Steel for $14.9 billion ($55 per share). The deal includes a $565 million breakup fee.\n- **January 11, 2024**: Bloomberg News reports that regulatory scrutiny is expected to extend the dealmaking process into late 2024 or 2025.\n- **March 14, 2024**: The Biden Administration officially opposes the acquisition, citing national security risks.\n- **April 2024**: U.S. Steel shareholders approve the deal, with over 98% voting in favor.\n- **May 2024**: Both companies announce they have received all non-U.S. regulatory approvals (from Mexico, Serbia, Slovakia, Turkey, the UK, and the EU).\n- **September 2024**: It is reported that the Biden Administration is preparing to block the proposed acquisition.\n- **January 3, 2025**: President Joe Biden blocks the deal via an executive order.\n- **January 6, 2025**: Nippon Steel and U.S. Steel sue the Biden administration.\n- **January 12, 2025**: The Biden administration delays the effective date of the block to June 18, 2025, to allow courts time to review the lawsuit.\n- **January 2025**: Activist investor Ancora Holdings launches a proxy battle against U.S. Steel, seeking to end the Nippon merger and replace CEO David Burritt.\n- **May 23, 2025**: President Donald Trump announces a revised "planned partnership" between U.S. Steel and Nippon Steel, reversing his earlier opposition.\n- **June 18, 2025**: The acquisition is finalized. U.S. Steel becomes a wholly owned subsidiary of Nippon Steel, and the U.S. government receives a "golden share." U.S. Steel is delisted from the New York Stock Exchange.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Latest Status Mentioned\n\nThe latest status is that the **acquisition was finalized on June 18, 2025**. The deal closed, U.S. Steel was delisted from the NYSE, and the U.S. government gained a "golden share" providing extensive control over the company.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Mention of "Golden Share" or Deal Finalization in June 2025\n\n- **Golden Share**: Yes. The article states: "On June 18, 2025, the acquisition was finalized, with the U.S. government gaining a golden share and extensive control over the company." It also notes that the golden share allows the U.S. president to appoint one of three board members and provides veto authority over corporate decisions (e.g., moving HQ, changing the name, reducing investments, transferring jobs or production abroad).\n- **Deal Finalization in June 2025**: The article explicitly states the acquisition closed on **June 18, 2025**, and that this date was set after the Biden administration delayed the block order to that same date for court review.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Revised Deals or Agreements with the Trump Administration\n\nYes. On **May 23, 2025**, President Donald Trump announced a **revised "planned partnership"** between U.S. Steel and Nippon Steel. Under the new terms:\n- U.S. Steel would maintain its headquarters in Pittsburgh.\n- The company would be led by an **American CEO** with a board majority of **U.S. citizens**.\n- The U.S. government would receive a **golden share** giving the president veto authority over key corporate decisions.\n- Nippon Steel committed to invest **$14 billion** into U.S. operations, including $2.4 billion for facilities in Pennsylvania\'s Mon Valley region.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Details on How U.S. Steel Addressed the Merger\n\n- **Initial Announcement**: U.S. Steel held a joint press conference with Nippon Steel on December 18, 2023, announcing the deal. CEO David Burritt indicated to shareholders the deal would close by spring/summer 2024.\n- **Shareholder Approval**: In April 2024, over 98% of U.S. Steel shareholders voted in favor of the acquisition.\n- **Legal Action**: On January 6, 2025, U.S. Steel (jointly with Nippon Steel) sued the Biden administration over the block of the merger.\n- **Warning on Alternatives**: In early 2025, U.S. Steel warned that if the Nippon deal collapsed, it **may close plants and shift production to lower-cost facilities**.\n- **Response to Proxy Battle**: U.S. Steel argued that the proxy battle launched by Ancora Holdings (which sought to end the Nippon merger) was a "low-cost and uncertain transaction with possible antitrust ramifications."\n- **Advisors**: U.S. Steel retained financial advisors (Goldman Sachs, Evercore, Barclays) and legal advisors (Milbank LLP, Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen & Katz) for the deal. It also hired lobbying firms K&L Gates and Hogan Lovells.',
