        args='{"prompt": "I need to understand exactly how US Steel has addressed the planned Nippon Steel merger and its effect on business operations, as stated in US Steel\'s own official filings. Please extract from these documents:\\n\\n1. From the 10-K annual report (2024), what does US Steel say about:\\n   - Risk factors related to the merger\\n   - How the merger has affected or may affect business operations\\n   - Costs incurred related to the merger\\n   - Any warnings about what might happen if the deal fails\\n\\n2. From the January 3, 2025 8-K filing (about the block), what did US Steel say about:\\n   - The Biden administration\'s decision\\n   - Their response/legal actions\\n   - The effect on business\\n\\n3. From the DEFA14A filings (Feb 2024, Mar 2025), what did US Steel say to stockholders about:\\n   - The benefits of the merger\\n   - Nippon Steel\'s commitments (investments, jobs, etc.)\\n   - The proxy fight/litigation status\\n\\nDocuments:\\n10-K: {{us_steel_10k_2024}}\\n8-K Jan 3 2025: {{us_steel_8k_nippon_block}}\\nDEFA14A Feb 2024: {{us_steel_defa14a_20240202}}\\nDEFA14A Mar 2025: {{us_steel_defa14a_20250325}}\\nDEFA14A Mar 26 2025: {{us_steel_defa14a_20250326}}\\n8-K May 2024: {{us_steel_8k_20240521}}"}',
        parsed_args={
            'prompt': "I need to understand exactly how US Steel has addressed the planned Nippon Steel merger and its effect on business operations, as stated in US Steel's own official filings. Please extract from these documents:\n\n1. From the 10-K annual report (2024), what does US Steel say about:\n   - Risk factors related to the merger\n   - How the merger has affected or may affect business operations\n   - Costs incurred related to the merger\n   - Any warnings about what might happen if the deal fails\n\n2. From the January 3, 2025 8-K filing (about the block), what did US Steel say about:\n   - The Biden administration's decision\n   - Their response/legal actions\n   - The effect on business\n\n3. From the DEFA14A filings (Feb 2024, Mar 2025), what did US Steel say to stockholders about:\n   - The benefits of the merger\n   - Nippon Steel's commitments (investments, jobs, etc.)\n   - The proxy fight/litigation status\n\nDocuments:\n10-K: {{us_steel_10k_2024}}\n8-K Jan 3 2025: {{us_steel_8k_nippon_block}}\nDEFA14A Feb 2024: {{us_steel_defa14a_20240202}}\nDEFA14A Mar 2025: {{us_steel_defa14a_20250325}}\nDEFA14A Mar 26 2025: {{us_steel_defa14a_20250326}}\n8-K May 2024: {{us_steel_8k_20240521}}"
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based solely on the provided excerpts from U.S. Steel’s official filings, here is a detailed breakdown of how the company has addressed the planned Nippon Steel merger.\n\n### 1. From the 10-K Annual Report (2024)\n\n**Risk factors related to the merger:**\n- **Failure to Complete:** The 10-K highlights the risk that the Merger may not close on time or at all, particularly due to the CFIUS process and the President’s January 3, 2025, order prohibiting it. It warns that a failure to close would negatively impact the business and stock price.\n- **Litigation:** The filing notes risks from "litigation related to the Merger, either brought by or against the parties."\n- **Management Distraction:** A key risk is "disruption of management time from ongoing business operations due to the Merger and related litigation."\n- **Operational Restrictions:** The 10-K states that the Merger Agreement restricts the company from taking certain actions "without the consent of Purchaser," which "may prevent us from pursuing otherwise attractive business opportunities."\n- **Negative Reactions:** Risks are cited concerning adverse reactions from customers, suppliers, and employees, including the potential departure of key personnel.\n\n**How the merger has affected or may affect business operations:**\n- **Restrictions on Operations:** “The Merger Agreement requires us to operate in the ordinary course of business and restricts us, without the consent of Purchaser, from taking certain specified actions agreed by the parties to be outside the ordinary course of business until the pending Merger occurs.”\n- **Diversion of Resources:** “matters relating to the Merger (including integration planning) will require substantial commitments of time and resources by our management, which could divert their time and attention.”\n- **Impact on Strategic Moves:** The agreement contains "customary limitations on U. S. Steel’s ability to engage in such transactions [like acquisitions, divestitures] without the consent of Purchaser" and also prohibits additional share repurchases and certain debt incurrence.\n\n**Costs incurred related to the merger:**\n- The 10-K lists "Strategic alternatives review process costs" of **$90 million** in 2024 (up from $79 million in 2023) as a specific line item in the segment reconciliation.\n- It further states under "Contingencies and Commitments": “We have incurred and expect to continue to incur significant expenses in connection with the pending Merger, including legal and investment banking fees.”\n\n**Any warnings about what might happen if the deal fails:**\n- **Stock Price Impact:** “we may experience negative reactions from the financial markets, including negative impacts on the market price of our common stock.”\n- **Loss of Management Focus:** “some of management’s attention will have been directed to the Merger instead of being directed to our own operations and the pursuit of other opportunities.”\n- **Harm to Business Relationships:** “the manner in which customers, suppliers and other third parties perceive us may be negatively impacted, which in turn could affect our ability to compete for business.”\n- **Loss of Nippon Steel’s Commitments:** “we will not obtain the benefits of NSC’s commitments to the Company, including the commitments to invest at least $2.7 billion of capital and to share technology to protect and grow the Company.”\n- **Wasted Time and Resources:** “we will have expended time and resources that could otherwise have been spent on our business.”\n\n---\n\n### 2. From the January 3, 2025 8-K Filing (about the block)\n\n**What U.S. Steel said about the Biden administration\'s decision:**\n- “We are dismayed by President Biden’s decision to block Nippon Steel’s acquisition of U. S. Steel, which reflects a clear violation of due process and the law governing CFIUS.”\n- “Instead of abiding by the law, the process was manipulated to advance President Biden’s political agenda.”\n- “The President’s statement and Order do not present any credible evidence of a national security issue, making clear that this was a political decision.”\n\n**Their response/legal actions:**\n- “Following President Biden’s decision, we are left with no choice but to take all appropriate action to protect our legal rights.”\n- They announced a joint lawsuit: “On January 6, 2025, the Company, NSC and Purchaser jointly filed a lawsuit in the United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit alleging that the President’s order blocking the Merger was issued for purely political reasons...”\n- They also filed a second lawsuit: “On the same day, the Company, NSC and Purchaser also filed a lawsuit in the United States District Court for the Western District of Pennsylvania against Cleveland-Cliffs Inc. (“Cliffs”), Cliffs’ Chief Executive Officer Lourenco Goncalves, and the President of the United Steelworkers... for engaging in a coordinated series of anticompetitive and racketeering activities...”\n\n**The effect on business:**\n- U.S. Steel stated that blocking the transaction “denies billions of committed investment to extend the life of U. S. Steel’s aging facilities and putting thousands of good-paying, family-sustaining union jobs at risk.”\n- The filing expresses the company’s belief that: “Nippon Steel is the only partner both willing and able to make the necessary investments – including at least $1 billion to Mon Valley Works and approximately $300 million to Gary Works as a part of $2.7 billion in investment that it has already committed.”\n\n---\n\n### 3. From the DEFA14A Filings (Feb 2024, Mar 2025)\n\n**What U.S. Steel said to stockholders about the benefits of the merger:**\n- The February 2024 filing emphasizes that the deal “DELIVERS CERTAIN AND IMMEDIATE VALUE FOR U. S. STEEL SHAREHOLDERS” at **$55.00 per share**, representing a **142% premium** to the unaffected stock price.\n- The March 2025 filing (proxy letter) states the Board conducted a “robust strategic alternatives review process... culminating in the value-maximizing transaction with Nippon Steel at $55 per share, representing a 142% premium.”\n- The benefits are framed as “Pro-Competitive,” “Pro-National Security,” “Pro-Employee,” and “Pro-Community.”\n\n**Nippon Steel\'s commitments (investments, jobs, etc.):**\n- **Investments:** “Nippon Steel will... make the necessary investments – including at least $1 billion to Mon Valley Works and approximately $300 million to Gary Works as a part of **$2.7 billion in investment** that it has already committed.”\n- **Job Commitments:** “Committed to zero layoffs, idled plants or permanent closures as a result of the transaction.” They also committed to “Creating up to ~5,000 temporary construction jobs by the $1 billion investment committed by Nippon Steel to modernize Mon Valley Works.”\n- **Honoring Labor Agreements:** “Nippon Steel will assume all USW agreements, including collective bargaining agreements.”\n- **Employee Bonuses:** “$5,000 closing bonus for every represented U. S. Steel employee and every eligible non-represented employee.”\n\n**The proxy fight/litigation status (as of March 2025):**\n- The filing describes a proxy contest launched by “Ancora Holdings Group” to replace the Board and CEO.\n- U.S. Steel characterizes Ancora’s nominees as “unqualified” and having “connections to a U. S. Steel competitor [Cleveland-Cliffs].”\n- **Litigation Status:** “As part of this Board’s commitment to delivering $55 in cash per share... we are pursuing all available options, including our joint legal action with Nippon Steel to obtain a fair, objective government national security review.”\n- **Litigation Strategy:** The filing notes that the litigation “extend[s] the process to allow for an agreement or unbiased review under the new administration.”',
