ction Jobs** | Up to ~5,000 temporary construction jobs from the $1 billion investment at Mon Valley Works |\\n| **Technology Sharing** | Enhanced technologies and resources to support a stronger, more competitive US steel industry |\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 4. Effect on Business Operations\\n\\n### A. Financial Impact\\n\\nUS Steel\'s 2024 annual results showed material impacts:\\n\\n- **Net earnings** declined to **$384 million** in 2024, from **$895 million** in 2023, a decrease of 57.1%.\\n- **Net sales** fell to **$15.6 billion** in 2024, down 13.4% from $18.1 billion in 2023.\\n- **Strategic alternatives review costs** totaled **$90 million** in 2024 (up from $79 million in 2023), representing legal, investment banking, and advisory fees related to the merger process.\\n- The company stated it \\"incurred and expect[s] to continue to incur significant expenses in connection with the pending Merger.\\"\\n\\n### B. Operational Restrictions\\n\\nThe Merger Agreement imposed significant limitations on US Steel\'s day-to-day operations:\\n\\n- **Ordinary course limitation:** \\"The Merger Agreement requires us to operate in the ordinary course of business and restricts us, without the consent of Purchaser, from taking certain specified actions agreed by the parties to be outside the ordinary course of business until the pending Merger occurs.\\"\\n- **Inability to pursue alternatives:** US Steel was prevented from pursuing \\"otherwise attractive business opportunities,\\" including acquisitions, divestitures, share repurchases, and certain debt incurrence without Nippon Steel\'s consent.\\n- **Management distraction:** \\"Matters relating to the Merger (including integration planning) will require substantial commitments of time and resources by our management, which could divert their time and attention\\" from ongoing business operations.\\n\\n### C. Risks if the Deal Fails\\n\\nUS Steel\'s 10-K filing warned of several negative consequences if the merger is not complet